* Article: LAKHANI Karim R. & WOLF, Robert G. (2005) ¨Why Hackers Do What They Do: Understanding Motivation and Effort in Free/Open Source Software Projects¨ en J. Feller, B. Fitzgerald, S. Hissam, & K. R. Lakhani, Perspectives on Free and Open Source Software MIT Press, Mass.


=Summary=

Mathieu O'Neil:

"A valuable reference is a study (Lakhani and Wolf, 2005) which, taking a sample of 680 cases of free software
producers, allows us to compare paid and voluntary developers. Predictably, the dedication to develop–measured
by hours- of those who receive monetary compensation is greater than the dedication of those who do not,
although the difference is not so great ( Lakhani & Wolf, 2005: Table 3). In turn, according to the study, 37.69%
of individuals developed because of request of the company to which they belonged. Previous studies provide
similar numbers (Hars and Ou 2002; Hertel, Niedner, and Herrmann 2003). In contrast, the 45.55% produced
free software outside working hours. Interestingly, however, there is a third set of developers who produced open
source software within their working hours, but without the consent of their supervisors. The latter group
exemplifies what we have recently noted: the existence of corporate employees who, according to their
philosophical identification or their belief in the efficiency of free software or others, develop open source
software without an order or a decision from the company."
(http://cspp.oekonux.org/scientific-committee/latest-submissions/regular-issue-p2p-theory/Collaborative%20production.pdf/at_download/file)


